data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — the most common `Thread.Abort` migration. Here's the full breakdown.

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`). The entire preemptive-kill model is removed.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload for new callers
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works if `work` checks the token. `Task.Run` won't kill a CPU-bound loop that ignores cancellation — the task keeps running, you just stop waiting. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers. Always `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking on async** | The sync overload uses `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` — safe here since `Task.Run` offloads work, but prefer the async overload for new code. |

## If `work` Is Truly Uncooperative

If you cannot modify `work` to accept a `CancellationToken` (e.g., third-party library doing blocking I/O), **no in-process mechanism can forcibly stop it**. Your options:

```csharp
// Option: Move uncooperative work to a child process you can kill
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

## Making `work` Cooperate (Best Practice)

Refactor callers to pass a `CancellationToken` through:

```csharp
// Before: executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => Compute(data), timeout);
// After:
await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    () => Compute(data, cts.Token), timeout);

// Inside Compute:
void Compute(Data data, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var item in data.Items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
}
```

The fundamental shift: .NET Framework let you kill threads externally; .NET 8 requires code to **volunteer to be cancelled**.
